story:
PIXITE invites you to enjoy an evening of fun and entertainment at our Halloween Ball on Saturday 29 October 2022. This free event is being held to raise funds for Cancer Reserarch UK and MSF Doctors without Borders.

Attendance at the ball is free of charge and guests are being asked to consider a voluntary donation to our deserving charities. 

You have chosen to donate to Cancer Research UK.

Cancer Research UK is the world’s leading cancer charity dedicated to saving lives through research, influence and information. They support research into all aspects of cancer through the work of over 4,000 scientists, doctors and nurses. This pioneering work into the prevention, diagnosis and treatment of cancer has helped save millions of lives.

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
Jake here, mild mannered vegetarian and family man.

I’m boxing to raise funds for Cancer Research - if I’d thought about this properly I’d have done a marathon, or some sort of hike but my knees aren’t that good… and I’m commîtes now. Unlike a marathon the suffering is hopefully over in 3 x 2 minute rounds. Also unlike a marathon coming second is not a desirable outcome.

For those of you who know me, you’ll appreciate that not being a fighter,  and I am nervous about this! So the motivation of raising money for a good cause is making this all worth while. Please donate it only takes a minute.

Official blurb below…

story:
In loving memory of a wonderful colleague and friend who was taken far too soon as she still had so much to give.

Val was an inspiration to us all, with her infectious smile and always a twinkle in her eyes. 

She was everyones friend, admired by all, such a popular lady who everyone wanted to be around. 

Val was always thoughtful and put others before herself. We can follow her example and keep her memory alive in our smiles. 

Val loved flowers, but wanted something good to come of her memory and as such her and Colin have asked that we support Cancer Research. 

Please donate as much or as little as you wish to her preferred charity via this Just Giving page.


Thanks for taking the time to visit this JustGiving page. Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I turned 40 this year and wanted to do something different, something i have never done before. Not going to lie but I have a fear of heights so I thought it would be a good idea to raise a few pounds in aid of a charity that needs support.

My Mum has lung cancer and is stable at the moment with her current treatment but unfortunately the treatment isn’t going to make the cancer go away. This is why i would like to raise any amount I can to make a difference not just for my mum but for others that are also suffering from cancer. 

So on the 5th of November around 12pm in Devon  me and my good friend Chris will be skydiving at the height of 15000 feet. If you can spare any amount we would be grateful. 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

eventName: Save the Children's Christmas Jumper Day 2022
story:
We're taking part in Save the Children's Christmas Jumper Day on Thursday 8 December and this year, its going to be twice as good as ever before!

Thats because the government has promised to give the same amount as you give this Christmas Jumper Day*. Double the funds, double the fun!

Just click the Give Now button above to donate £2 (or more if you're feeling generous...) and the UK government will double it. We've also got our own QR code: just scan the code with your phone camera and donate to our team!

So donate now and help us reach our target.

By pulling on our Christmassy knits and donating, we'll be helping mums and babies stay healthy, and giving them the chance of the future they deserve.

Just £20 could buy antibiotics to help ten children beat malnutrition.

eventName: Save the Children's Christmas Jumper Day 2022
story:
We're taking part in Save the Children's Christmas Jumper Day on Thursday 8 December and this year, its going to be twice as good as ever before!

Thats because the government has promised to give the same amount as you give this Christmas Jumper Day*. Double the funds, double the fun!

Just click the Give Now button above to donate £2 (or more if you're feeling generous...) and the UK government will double it. We've also got our own QR code: just scan the code with your phone camera and donate to our team!

So donate now and help us reach our target.

By pulling on our Christmassy knits and donating, we'll be helping mums and babies stay healthy, and giving them the chance of the future they deserve.

Just £20 could buy antibiotics to help ten children beat malnutrition.

charity.description: Save the Children exists to help every child reach their full potential. In the UK and around the world, we make sure children stay safe, healthy and keep learning, so they can become who they want to be.
charity.name: Save the Children
eventName: Save the Children's Christmas Jumper Day 2022
story:
We're taking part in Save the Children's Christmas Jumper Day on Thursday 8 December and this year, its going to be twice as good as ever before!

Thats because the government has promised to give the same amount as you give this Christmas Jumper Day*. Double the funds, double the fun!

Just click the Give Now button above to donate £2 (or more if you're feeling generous...) and the UK government will double it. We've also got our own QR code: just scan the code with your phone camera and donate to our team!

So donate now and help us reach our target.

By pulling on our Christmassy knits and donating, we'll be helping mums and babies stay healthy, and giving them the chance of the future they deserve.

Just £20 could buy antibiotics to help ten children beat malnutrition.

story:
We're taking part in Save the Children's Christmas Jumper Day on Thursday 8 December and this year, its going to be twice as good as ever before!

Thats because the government has promised to give the same amount as you give this Christmas Jumper Day*. Double the funds, double the fun!

Just click the Give Now button above to donate £2 (or more if you're feeling generous...) and the UK government will double it. We've also got our own QR code: just scan the code with your phone camera and donate to our team!

So donate now and help us reach our target.

By pulling on our Christmassy knits and donating, we'll be helping mums and babies stay healthy, and giving them the chance of the future they deserve.

Just £20 could buy antibiotics to help ten children beat malnutrition.

donate, volunteer, raise money or campaign with us, call 0300 1000 200 or visit macmillan.org.uk

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
In April 2023 I will be taking on the massive challenge of running The London Marathon. I was lucky to gain a ballot place to run the 2022 London Marathon, and I’m so excited to have the opportunity to do it all again in 2023, this time raising funds for Macmillan Cancer Support.

Macmillan is here to help everyone with cancer to live life as fully as they can, by providing emotional, physical, practical and financial support.

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan gives people with cancer everything they’ve got. If you’re diagnosed, your worries are Macmillan’s worries. Macmillan’s doing whatever it takes. But without your help, Macmillan can’t support everyone who needs them. Please give what you can. Your support will make a massive difference and will really help me get to the finish line 😊

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe, JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

story:
The NSPCC is the leading children's charity fighting to end child abuse in the UK and Channel Islands. We help children who have been abused to rebuild their lives, protect those at risk, and find the best ways of preventing abuse from ever happening.

Every child deserves the best possible chance to rebuild their life after abuse

That’s why we’re here. That's what drives all our work. And that’s why – as long as there’s abuse – we will fight for every childhood.

charity.name: RSPCA (England and Wales)
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.  

For those who know me I thoroughly enjoy exercise with the exception of running.  I do run, because I know it is good for me but these are just park runs 5k weekly... I have  never run further than 10k so this will be interesting!  There are a number of things I would like to achieve in my lifetime, the London Half is one of those.  This event will be a challenge to me and I hope that will inspire you to donate anything big or small to help me get over that line!!  

There are a number of charities I have raised money for in the past and have chosen the RSPCA for my LLHM because it is astonishing how much animal cruelty happens across the country (and wider).  The RSPCA require funding to continue aiding those creatures who do not have a voice.  I hope I can reach my target to offer a difference in the work they do.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description:
The Salvation Army is a Christian Church & registered Charity working in 130 countries worldwide and is one of the largest and most diverse providers of social welfare in the world. In the UK and Republic of Ireland this work includes more than 800 Salvation Army social service centres and
Community churches. We provide unconditional friendship, support and very practical help to people in crisis and need and work with children, homeless people, all adult victims of modern slavery and those dealing with drug and/or alcohol addiction. Alongside our work in the UK, The Salvation Army International Projects Office works with communities around the world to support and empower them to defeat poverty and injustice. Our development projects are created and implemented in partnership with communities to enable them to build a better life and future for themselves. 
The Salvation Army is a Christian Church & registered Charity in England (214779), Wales (214779), Scotland (SC009359) and the Republic of Ireland (CHY6399)
charity.name: The Salvation Army
story:
Every year at Christmas, The Salvation Army in Stirling provides toys, gifts and food for families and the elderly who are in financial difficulty.  These children are referred to us by professional support workers both in health and education settings and social services.  Last year we provided Christmas to 150 families in Stirling.  This year we expect this number to be far higher!

The Salvation Army's Christmas Present Appeal makes a huge difference to hundreds of children across Stirling by making sure they receive a gift on Christmas Day instead of missing out.  This year with the effects of the Cost of Living Crisis, we especially need your help to ensure no child is neglected this Christmas.  

Could you help us make Christmas Special for those who have little or
nothing on the table this Christmas?  The Salvation Army in Stirling is also raising money to ensure that the poorest families can receive a Christmas dinner this year.  Through our Meal Appeal we aim to provide Christmas dinner for pensioners and families who otherwise may not be able to afford a Christmas meal.  A donation of £20 will provide them with a 3 course Christmas meal & a small gift.

Be a Star this Christmas and help those that need it most.
title: Christmas Present & Meal Appeal
pageSummary: Please help us raise funds because every family deserves a Christmas

eventName: Cheltenham Christmas Toy and Food Parcel Appeal 2022
owner: The Salvation Army Community Church Cheltenham
story:
At Christmas, more than any other time, The Salvation Army works tirelessly for people in need. Homeless and hungry people, families facing hardship, victims of domestic abuse and human trafficking, people who are ill or grieving, people who are desperately lonely - we reach out to all of them with unstinting friendship and practical, professional help. 

Here's how your donations could transform lives this Christmas in Cheltenham...

This year working in partnership with local agencies we are seeking to support over 500 families with our Food and Toy Appeal. All donations are used locally here in the Cheltenham area both at Christmas and throughout the rest of the year. Your donation however small will make a difference and will be so gratefully received. 

Thank you and God Bless you!
title: The Cheltenham Salvation Army Christmas Toy and Food Parcel Appeal 2022

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support.  My best friend of almost 40 years died suddenly at the end of May 2022 from a massive heart attack.  B was a very good friend,  godfather to my children and an honorary member of our family.  We had both taken up running in the past few years in an attempt to get a bit fitter and lighter in a vain attempt to stave off old age.  Sadly  B will be forever young...ish so in his memory, and to raise money for the British Heart Foundation, I have decided to enter the GNR, something B would never have considered.  Hopefully you will give a donation.

charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
Hi,

My name is Nicholas Wasunna, I work for UNICEF, having been posted in a number of duty stations I am currently posted in Yemen. I see on a daily basis how tough things are for the children here in the midst of the ongoing conflict. UNICEF are delivering some really great projects and initiatives which are making such a big difference in the lives of children here. In Yemen a child dies every 10 minutes from preventable causes.

This is such vital work and I want to support them as much as I possibly can … so I have decided to run the New York marathon on 6 November to try and raise more funds. I know that times are hard for many, particularly at the moment, so would greatly appreciate any donations people felt able to make. I feel somewhat daunted about taking on the marathon but feel really motivated knowing that every penny I raise will go directly to helping children that truly need it. 

Thank you so very much.

Nick.

charity.description: Every day 250 people in the UK start losing their sight. With your help, we can be there when people need us most, support independent living, create an inclusive society and prevent avoidable sight loss. Every pound you raise will help create a future where sight loss is no longer a barrier.
charity.name: RNIB - Royal National Institute of Blind People
story:
I am running the London Marathon for the first time on Sunday 23rd April 2023 and I am fortunate enough to do it for a great charity in RNIB. My amazing Nan has suffered from loss of sight the majority of her life and to run for this charity means a lot to me and my family. 

Thanks for your support with my London Marathon challenge!Every day, 250 people in the UK start losing their sight. Too many still face isolation and depression, unable to achieve their potential in a world that blocks their way. RNIB wont stop until every last psychological and physical barrier has gone for good.With your help, RNIB can be there when people need them most, support independent living, create an inclusive society and prevent avoidable sight loss. Every pound you donate is helping create a future where sight loss is no longer a barrier.£20 could help someone feel more confident about living with sight loss, with personalised support from our expert Sight Loss Advice Service. £47 could help someone feel more positive about the future after losing their sight, through a one-to-one phone or online counselling session. £2,500 could make a new adult book available in our Talking Books library, enabling a person with sight loss to enjoy the latest best seller.

charity.description: We're a Christian aid and development agency, following Jesus to the places of greatest need to respond to disasters and help communities unlock their own potential to overcome poverty. We won't stop until poverty stops.
charity.name: Tearfund
story:
The money you raise will transform the lives of people like Zuleima. 

Zuleima is a 35-year-old mother of three from Venezuela. It is a country struggling beneath the weight of a massive economic crisis. 

Along with more than a million other Venezuelans, Zuleima made the decision to flee to neighbouring Colombia. [I was] leaving my house, my home, my memories, Zuleima says, It was very difficult to leave it all behind.

The church opened their doors, and they helped me, says Zuleima. Not only giving me food and a place to live, but also taking care of my emotions, giving me words of hope, giving me words of faith.

As well as providing support for refugees immediate needs, Tearfunds local church partners have been setting up support groups that help people like Zuleima find new income opportunities. 

A gift of £24 could provide two women like Zuliema with the training and tools they need to provide a better future for their families

charity.description:
ActionAid is an international humanitarian charity that works with women and girls living in poverty.

Our dedicated local staff are changing the world with women and girls. We are ending violence and fighting poverty so that all women, everywhere, can create the future they want.
charity.name: ActionAid
story:
This November, I am taking part in The 137 Challenge with ActionAid. Did you know, one in three women will experience some form of violence in their lifetime, and 137 women are killed per day by a partner or family member? Donating just £23 could pay a counsellors salary for a month meaning women and girls who have survived violence have access to crucial psychosocial support to help them recover. ActionAid is an international charity that works with women and girls living in poverty. Their dedicated local staff are changing the world with women and girls. They are ending violence and fighting poverty so that all women, everywhere can create the future they want. If you'd like to find out more about the amazing work ActionAid does, please visit their website at www.actionaid.org.uk.

I've been through domestic violence, I was lucky...I survived and got a second chance.

I appreciate times are hard, if you can make a donation it is very much appreciated 🥰.
title: The 137 Challenge 2022
pageSummary: I am doing a daily challenge in November because I want to my bit to help others.

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story: Guide Dogs wouldn't be here without you. Our life-changing services depend on donations. In the UK, one more person loses their sight every six minutes. The money you raise will help us train up more puppies, and transform the life of someone with sight loss. We've set you a fundraising target of just £125. That's enough to give a new guide dog owner a Starter Kit to help their life with a guide dog.
title: Leo’s page

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

story:
David Edwards (July 13, 1951 - October 15, 2022) was a proud Scotsman, husband, father, grandfather and friend to many who started to lose his sight over 30 years ago. He was also a runner...

Despite his disability David was a veteran of over 200 parkruns and competed in events such as The Virtual London Marathon and Great South Run with his guides, John Baker and Cliffe Tribe.

He was an avid campaigner for the Guide Dogs Charity and will be remembered for his loyalty, spirit, generosity and courage. 

The challenge on November 20, 2022 at the Wimborne 10, a ten mile road race, will involve Cliffe being fully blindfolded and guided by John in tribute and in memory to a great friend and running companion.
title: David's Guide - A 10 mile blindfold run in memory of a friend

story:
Salam as a part of Newcastle ISoc, I am organising a bike ride on 30 October to the beach for the sake of Charity Week. Charity Week is an amazing initiative, and I am grateful that I have the opportunity to be involved. Newcastle ISoc is fundraising for children and orphans in need all around the world. charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
This winter I'll be taking part in Brave the Chill in aid of WWF. Sponsor me to help WWF bring our world back to life.

Climate change poses the biggest threat to the future of our planet. Global temperatures have been rising for over a century and are now the highest on record. One landscape the climate crisis has put into meltdown is the Arctic, with this polar region warming almost three times faster than the global average. It may seem a bit chilly for some of us, but the Arctic is crucial for lots of reasons.

Polar bears and walrus call this freezing landscape their home. But their environment is changing, because of global warming. The sea ice during the summer months is declining, and with global warming, that ice is shrinking fast.

By sponsoring me to Brave the Chill, together we can help bring our world back to life.

charity.name: Barnardo's
story:
My lovely Dad was an absolute legend. An inspiration for sure. Such a kind, gentle and loving man. 

Dad was sent to Barnados aged 8 at the start of the war because his Mum couldn’t cope with 3 children (absent father). His brother and sister remained at home. He was affected by this decision for the rest if his life. 

Dad taught me many things. Honesty, integrity, drive and ambition. A love of life. Regret nothing. Love hard. 

I miss him dearly. I will keep my promise to him, even though my body doesn’t seem capable. 

If you are able to donate to Barnados, to help me keep running it would be amazing -THANK YOU! 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.
title: Dawn's Half Marathon 30-Oct

charity.description: Barnardo’s is the UK’s largest national children’s charity. In 2019-20, we supported work with 358,800 children, young people, parents and carers, across more than 800 services and partnerships throughout the UK.
charity.name: Barnardo's
story:
Thank you for taking the time to even tap the link and look at my fundraising page! In all honesty running a marathon is not something I ever thought I would do, I am not a runner or a work out enthusiast in any shape or form! But life takes you on different journeys, some you never thought you would be on and well that’s what has lead me to right here, right now, training for a marathon. 

In September 2019 I became a mum for the first time to a beautiful little boy, Leo. He is now 3 years old and the happiest, cheekiest, most affectionate little boy who I absolutely adore! My journey into motherhood didn’t start as planned, the world decided to have a pandemic and well goodbye to social groups and having the most fun with Leo and our friends and family. Coming out of lockdown I knew Leo wasn’t hitting all his “milestones”, he doesn’t clap, point, wave, he struggles with eye contact and is non-verbal, but of course at the time as any parent does I made every excuse under the sun. Until it came to Leo’s second birthday, I couldn’t keep hiding what I knew was coming, I needed to speak up. From September 2021 we have been on the journey of Leo being diagnosed with Autism.  It has been a rollercoaster of a journey, so many appointments, so many observations, it isn’t just a one day, one person diagnosis. It is ALOT and it can be lonely. Autism isn’t something I knew much about and my god am I still learning, but to explain it to people of why Leo is the way he is sometimes is hard. But along this journey I have had amazing support, I have made some lifelong friends who are in the same position and it has been nice to finally be able to turn to another parent on this journey. Part of that is down to Barnados. The support they have given to us and the parent support class we attended was honestly amazing, the time, effort and care they put in I couldn’t be more grateful and so this is my way of just saying thank you for all the hard work they do for children and families not just in our situation but just in general life with how the world is currently. I really couldn’t thank them enough for their love and support. So here I am taking myself out of my comfort zone, into the unknown and on a rollercoaster of a journey, something Leo and lots of other children deal with everyday. 

Any donation amount you can spare will be really appreciated by myself and the charity who do so much to support children and families. Thank you in advance for your support ❤️

story:
Every year our babyballet® stars across the UK absolutely love attending their classes in their pyjamas, in the week leading up to BBCs Children In Need.

We dance, skip, hop and sing at class, all while wearing pyjamas and we ask our wonderful babyballet® grown ups to donate what they can.

charity.description:
Every day, men and women have to leave their career in the Armed Forces as a result of physical or psychological wounds. 
Your fundraising helps them recover and get on with their lives. So far we've supported more than 25,000 people and won’t stop until every veteran gets the support they deserve.
charity.name: Help for Heroes
story:
Im proud to support Help for Heroes - because I believe our Armed Forces community should live well after service.

Can you imagine how tough life can be when a military career comes to an end, especially if it has been cut short by illness or injury. Overnight, you lose not only your job, but also a support network that is like family. 

This is why I stand with Help for Heroes.

There are many ways the Charity helps veterans, their loved ones, serving personnel, and people who worked alongside the UK military. From helping people with their physical and mental health. To giving people the support, skills, confidence, and knowledge to make a success of life in the civilian world.  

Its an injustice that people dont get a fair deal from the country they risked everything for. Help for Heroes wont stop until those who served to keep us safe get the support they deserve.

story:
I’m proud to support Help for Heroes - because I believe our Armed Forces community should live well after service.

Can you imagine how tough life can be when a military career comes to an end, especially if it has been cut short by illness or injury. Overnight, you lose not only your job, but also a support network that is like family.

This is why I stand with Help for Heroes.

There are many ways the Charity helps veterans, their loved ones, serving personnel, and people who worked alongside the UK military. From helping people with their physical and mental health. To giving people the support, skills, confidence, and knowledge to make a success of life in the civilian world.

It’s an injustice that people don’t get a fair deal from the country they risked everything for. Help for Heroes won’t stop until those who served to keep us safe get the support they deserve.
title: Howzzat's Help for Heroes Fundraising Page

story:
WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.

Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.

charity.name: Alzheimer's Society
story:
A Good Walk Interrupted

At the beginning of the year, I was unfit and decided I needed to lose some weight, I needed to set myself a long-term target. I did the maths and worked out that 5 million steps in a year was an achievable target but also a stretch. There are days when circumstances just do not allow too many steps. I also wanted to raise some money for a good cause. Knowing a few people who have been affected by Alzheimer’s Disease I think there is no more a worthy cause. So off I set…….

Come Easter Bank Holiday month, I had lost two stone in weight and was ahead of target having walked over 1.9 million steps, I was really enjoying the challenge, and a weekend at our caravan always afforded nice walks. The day started, as it has done many times with a walk around the sea wall with our dog, Rocco…except I didn’t make it back to the caravan. I stepped off a shallow ledge straight into a pothole covered by the overgrown grass, I felt my ankle rotate underneath me, and although I didn’t hear a snap, I knew immediately it was broken, within a couple of minutes I also had excruciating pain on the outside of my lower leg.

After a couple of hours, I was in a splint and carted off to hospital by ambulance. Looking at the X Rays, I heard the radiographer say, ‘it’s pretty messed up down there’, this was soon after validated when the consultant told me I had a broken tibia, broken fibula, and a ruptured deltoid ligament. My ankle was displaced and had to be reset which took two very painful attempts. I was booked in for ORIF surgery 9 days later to allow the swelling to subside.

I was laid up for over 7 weeks non weight bearing, I had plenty of time to recalculate how much the average step count was increasing if I was to cover 5 million steps and confess that as time went on, I thought it would be unachievable……but I am nothing but determined. I also had time to research how I could give myself the best chance. I didn’t know how quickly I would recover, and I didn’t know how far I would be able to walk but I could influence the acceleration of my recovery. I booked sessions with a physiotherapist who worked wonders and pushed me hard, at one point I was doing exercises totalling over 1,400 ankle/leg/foot movements a day. It was hard going, and it was painful but it was what I had to do. I was able to walk with crutches and a cam boot from June 8th and then I was approved for walking full weight bearing 2 weeks earlier than scheduled on June 29th, this gave me a boost, the hard work was starting to pay off. I managed 1,713 steps that day and it hurt a lot.

My positive mindset kicked in, I continued with physiotherapy and intense exercises to continue to improve my range of movement. I am not quite walking full pace or full stride and develop a slight limp after around 5,000 steps, I also have Plantar Fasciitis and have been told that my ankle will never be normal. It has been a long haul, but I am on target to break the 4 million steps milestone by the end of October, I will then have just under 1 million steps to walk in two months. I am not too confident walking in wet conditions or in the dark, but I am determined to reach the finishing line.

I always took walking for granted, it really hits you when you are immobile, it’s frustrating and whilst I will not be as agile as I was before the accident, I am fortunate to have recovered reasonably well. In context, Alzheimer’s disease is irreversible, it develops and worsens over time and severely impacts the lives of those who suffer and those around them. It is estimated that there are more than 850,000 people affected in the UK alone. Alzheimer’s Society relies on voluntary donations from the public, it provides much needed support services to those affected. The amazing work they do can be seen at Alzheimer's Society (alzheimers.org.uk). 

Any donations to this fantastic cause would be hugely appreciated.

Every step counts, every donation makes a difference.

Thank you for reading.

David

story:
Alzheimer’s Society is transforming the landscape of dementia forever.Until the day we find a cure, we will create a society where those affected by dementia are supported and accepted, able to live in their community without fear or prejudice.

I have never had good hand-eye coordination and have tried learning to juggle over the years but got frustrated and gave up. However as I have always wanted to learn, I am taking the 2 week challenge to learn to juggle for dementia in aid of the Alzheimer's society to help raise much needed funds and awareness to help individuals and their families who are going through a dementia diagnosis. Hopefully through fundraising, there will be better treatments and one day, a cure. Many thanks for reading, I hope you will consider supporting me in this challenge.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page

Some of you will no Paul & I’s journey with dementia and how it effected us greatly. 

Sadly I’ve met, cried and journeyed with others who have also gone through similar battles with this horrid disease.

People who have watched loved ones disappear, people who struggle to get support & help, people who would give the world for one more hour with missing memories. 

This disease effects not just the aged, it doesn’t just effect the less well off .. It has no boundaries on creed, gender, wealth.

Alzheimer’s UK is working hard to get some answers, working hard to get support for everyone who needs it.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.name: Alzheimer's Society
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page for Reiner. 

Alzheimer’s Society is here for everyone affected by dementia.

By 2025, 1 million people will be living with the condition in the UK, and many millions more carers, partners, families and friends are affected.

Lack of treatments and postcode lottery for care means that people with dementia and their families aren’t getting the support they need, when they need it.

We will not rest until people with dementia and their carers live more fulfilled and less fearful lives, free from stigma and inequality.

Our supporters ensure that people living with dementia today have the support they deserve, that their rights are protected and enhanced by campaigning, and that they can look to a brighter future thanks to investment in research.

story:
Ready, Set, SNOW! I'm unleashing my inner elf to support people affected by dementia.

This cause is very close to my heart after losing my grandad to it years before he actually fell asleep. It was heartbreaking to watch how dementia changed him and the pain it put all his family through while watching this terrible disease take him away.

Please dig deep and donate as much or as little as you can! Let’s get a cure or at least more research into finding one.

Many thanks in advance and so much love to you all that have been touched by this disease.

Gem x x x

charity.name: Alzheimer's Society
story:
On Friday 2nd decemeber Me, Harleigh and Greyson are all dressing up as elves, Harleigh will attend school all day dressed as an elf and greyson nursery.

I am going to drop harleigh to school, Greyson to nursery and then go into town to buy some special festive gifts which we are then going to give to some of the local food banks for gifts for children this Christmas.

Im hoping to spread some christmas cheer for the children this year while raising money for an amazing charity.

As little as 1p donation goes along way.

Alzheimer’s Society is close to my heart and i want to do my bit in memory of my beloved nan who was the glue to my family 💔

When my nan forgot who I was and other family members it was like loosing her for the first time, watching her slowly fade from the person we always knew and loved so very much. When nan lost her battle to Alzheimer’s it was even harder as it was like loosing her for a 2nd time all over again but this time only worse.

Thank you for reading my story.

charity.description:
Shelter works to alleviate the distress caused by homelessness and bad housing.  

We help people find and keep a home. We campaign for decent housing for all. Our work won’t stop until there’s a home for everyone.
charity.name: Shelter
story:
A home is a fundamental human need and a basic moral right, as vital as education or healthcare. But in Britain today, 3,500 people sleep on the streets on any given night and 113,000 households are stuck in temporary accommodation, such as homeless hostels.

We're partnering with Shelter to help get people who have been affected by homelessness back into work.

Thank you very much for your support.

charity.description:
Shelter works to alleviate the distress caused by homelessness and bad housing.  

We help people find and keep a home. We campaign for decent housing for all. Our work won’t stop until there’s a home for everyone.
charity.name: Shelter
story:
I am taking part in Walk for Home for Shelter this December to fight homelessness & unite against the housing emergency.

Thousands of people across the UK are going the distance this winter. It's been a difficult year & things have really hit home. But your sponsorship will do incredible things from supporting people whose jobs & homes are under threat to campaigning for a stronger safety net for everyone.

The money raised will help Shelter campaign to end rough sleeping, build more social homes & protect renters who face discrimination and eviction:

£10 could pay for two webchats of online support and advice.

£20 could pay for two calls through our emergency helpline.

£80 could pay for two face-to-face advice sessions.

£120 could pay for a legal advice session for someone facing housing problems.

£150 could help someone keep their home resolving a complex housing issue for them.

Thank you for making a big difference!

Thank you for making a big difference!

charity.name: Shelter
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

At Shelter, they understand more than most about the effects of the cost of living crisis. They are taking calls every day from people worried about being evicted, not being able to afford their rent, or having to choose between eating or heating. Fundraising enables them to fight for the right to a safe home for everyone. This winter will be tough for us all but even more so for those less fortunate than us so please help me raise as much as possible to help Shelter support as many people as possible.

charity.description: Our mission is to transform the quality of life for donkeys, mules and people worldwide through greater understanding, collaboration and support. We want a world where donkeys and mules live free from suffering and their contribution to humanity is fully valued.
charity.name: The Donkey Sanctuary
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I've set this page up in hope of donations for mums favourite charity. Sadly she passed away on  the 19th October 2022 leaving lots of memories for us but a huge hole in our lives. She had a soft spot for donkeys and over the last few years supported them as best she could. Even visiting some while she was very poorly and struggling to walk herself. 

If you can spare even a few pennies she would of been so happy to think that others also helped with the rescue and care of the donkeys. 


Thank you x

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description: Our mission is to transform the quality of life for donkeys, mules and people worldwide through greater understanding, collaboration and support. We want a world where donkeys and mules live free from suffering and their contribution to humanity is fully valued.
charity.name: The Donkey Sanctuary
story:
On the 14th October we lost lovely Lynnie.

In Memory of Lynne, Len and her family would welcome charitable donations to Lynne’s favourite charity The Donkey Sanctuary in Devon, a charitable foundation that Lynne supported and sponsored and visited. A life long animal lover, we thought that this would be a fitting tribute to our lovely Wife, Sister and Auntie.

Your kind donation is an amazing way to honour and remember Lynne, ensuring her memory lives on by transforming the lives of donkeys and communities across the world every single day.Your gift helps provide safe and loving homes for life for abandoned and abused animals rescued in the UK and Ireland. Overseas, your kindness makes a life-saving difference to donkeys and mules working with some of the worlds poorest communities. Its a wonderful way to both pay tribute to Lynne and support the rights of abused, neglected and abandoned donkeys across the world.

Thank you for your kindness.

❤️ Len ❤️

🐴 Sue&Richard 🐴 Anne&Brian 🐴 Philip 

🐴 Kate,Mark&Jack🐴

charity.description: Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation. We work in over 70 countries - in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. We are independent, neutral and impartial. We provide medical care where it's needed most.
charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
eventName: Pixite Halloween Ball 2022 - MSF Doctors without Borders
story:
PIXITE invites you to enjoy an evening of fun and entertainment at our Halloween Ball on Saturday 29 October 2022. This free event is being held to raise funds for Cancer Reserarch UK and MSF Doctors without Borders.

Attendance at the ball is free of charge and guests are being asked to consider a voluntary donation to our deserving charities. 

You have chosen to donate to Medecins Sans Frontieres (Doctors without Borders)

MSF Doctors without Borders are an international, medical humanitarian organisation working in more than 90 countries around the world. Their medical teams act fast to save people’s lives in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. 

Recent emergencies in Ukraine and Pakistan highlight the urgent need for their continued support and intervention.
